The paper proposes a deep learning approach for improving the quality of images obtained via dynamic contrast-enhanced MRI (DCE-MRI) that include motion artifacts and blurring. The method involves using a multi-channel convolutional neural network (MARC) for reducing the motion artifacts and blurring caused by respiratory motion in images obtained via DCE-MRI of the liver. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category for this paper is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). 

The paper also involves training datasets for the neural network, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the use of deep learning for image processing indicates that it may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. 

The paper also involves patient studies and the use of a T1-weighted spoiled gradient echo sequence, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. Finally, the use of a neural network for denoising and filtering suggests that it may also belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
